Usairpollution data consists of 41 US cities and has the following variables:

A data frame with 41 observations on the following 7 variables.

SO2: SO2 content of air in micrograms per cubic metre.

temp: average annual temperature in Fahrenheit.

manu: number of manufacturing enterprises employing 20 or more workers.

popul: population size (1970 census); in thousands.

wind: average annual wind speed in miles per hour.

precip: average annual precipitation in inches.

predays: average number of days with precipitation per year.

  • Chi Square QQ Plot shows an obvious indication of non-normality since almost all of the points are not close to the straight line. Also, from the outputs, we can check individual normality of the variables, only Wind and Predays variables follow normality.

  • Now, to check the multivariate normality officially, an official test should be conducted with the following hypothesis:

\[H_0: The\ data\ follows\ normal\ distribution.\ \] \[ H_1: The\ data\ does \ not\ follow\ a\ normal\ distribution.\ \]

 mvn(data = us, mvnTest = "hz")

  • Henze-Zirklers MVN test suggests non-normality with a very low p-value. We reject \[H_0\] Thus, there is enough evidence to conclude that the data is not normal at 95% confidence level.
for(i in 1:ncol(us)) {
  for(j in 1:ncol(us)) {
    if(i!=j){
      mvn(us[,c(i,j)],multivariatePlot ="qq")[4]
    }
  }
}

  • From the outputs, we see that some of the QQ-plot seem to be okay. This illustrates that individually, some of the variables are probably follow a normal distribution however when they are combined together, they do not follow a normal distribution.

  • Henze-Zirklers MVN test and Multivariate Normality QQ Plot are much more easy to interpret in terms of multivariate situation. It may be quite problematic to check all of the QQ Plot pairs if we would have for ex. 100 different variables. Then it would be impossible to look at all of them one by one.

result <- mvn(data = us, mvnTest = "royston", multivariateOutlierMethod = "adj",showNewData = TRUE,)

  • Adjusted Mahalanobis Distance suggests that there are 15 outliers in the data such as Chicago, Albuqerque, Phoenix, Denver.. . However, by manually, we have detected only 7 outliers above. Thus, probably, just by looking at the data as a whole, Adjusted Mahalanobis Distance was able to detect more outliers systematically.

  • It is quite problematic since total number of observation is quite low, 40 and approximately half of the observations are outliers.

  • This is probably due to the lower sample size.

  • If there were more cities to examine, it would be better to understand the relationship between these variables to understand the air pollution.

  • After removing all of the 15 outliers, do we have still non-normality problem? Let’s check.
